+# Local Property Storage
+
+## Architecture
+
+The upload feature uses the browser's IndexedDB API. This keeps the React demo
+self-contained while allowing listings and images to survive page reloads and
+browser restarts.
+
+![Exposé upload architecture and data flow](assets/expose-upload-architecture.png)
+
+`app/data/property-store.ts` owns persistence and exposes:
+
+- `usePropertyStore()` for reactive property, loading, and error state;
+- `createLocalProperty()` for publication;
+- `deleteLocalProperty()` for removal;
+- `refreshProperties()` for re-reading browser data.
+
+No additional npm package is required.
+
+## Database layout
+
+The database is named `estate-scout42`, currently at version `1`. It contains a
+single object store named `properties` with `id` as its key path.
+
+Local records use the shared `Property` shape plus metadata:
+
+| Field | Purpose |
+| --- | --- |
+| `id` | UUID generated at publication time |
+| `images` | Ordered image Data URLs; the first value is the cover |
+| `created_at` | ISO timestamp used to sort newest listings first |
+| `source` | Set to `local` for browser-created entries |
+
+Static JSON entries are normalized in memory with `source: "static"` and an
+`images` array containing their existing `main_image`. Static records are never
+written to IndexedDB.
+
+## Combined read model
+
+The store initially exposes static properties so the application remains
+useful while IndexedDB opens. It then loads local records, sorts them by
+creation time, and publishes a combined list:
+
+```text
+local properties, newest first
+static JSON properties, existing order
+```
+
+Search results, city options, and detail lookup consume this combined list.
+`My listings` consumes only `localProperties`.
+
+Subscribers are notified through `useSyncExternalStore`. Creating, deleting,
+or manually refreshing a record updates every mounted consumer without a page
+reload.
+
+## Slugs and identity
+
+Existing static properties keep their title-derived URL slug. Local properties
+append the first eight characters of their UUID:
+
+```text
+/exposes/bright-apartment-with-city-views-a1b2c3d4
+```
+
+This prevents two browser-created properties with identical titles from
+colliding while preserving old static URLs.
+
+## Image persistence
+
+The upload component reads accepted image files as Data URLs before
+publication. IndexedDB stores those strings inside the property record. This is
+simple and portable for a demo, but less space-efficient than binary Blob
+storage or an object-storage service.
+
+The UI limits uploads to 8 images and 5 MB per original file to reduce browser
+storage pressure. Actual quotas vary by browser, available disk space, and
+privacy mode.
+
+## Failures and recovery
+
+The store reports a readable error when IndexedDB is unavailable, blocked, or
+full. Quota errors recommend deleting a local listing or selecting smaller
+images.
+
+When loading local data fails, static properties remain visible. Failed writes
+do not redirect and leave the completed form available for correction or retry.
+Failed deletion leaves the listing visible and shows an error on `My listings`.
+
+Clearing site data is destructive and cannot be recovered because there is no
+server copy. A production implementation should replace this store with an
+authenticated API and external image storage.
